			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The beleaguered troll moved through the Dark Elf city with confidence, masking any inner trepidation brought about by the disapproving looks of his hosts. The stone floor reacted to the heavy impact of the jaundiced boned boots he wore with a shudder that echoed off of the walls of the underground city. Of course, should the favor of the blackened devils who were providing him solace ever wane, he'd be dead in an instant. He knew that uncertainty and intimidation often led to an early grave here, just as it did with his own kind. 
<br />

<br />
Without a glance to the guards he made his way to the Foreign Quarter. Thurgga, always the frisky one, shot him a devious grin. “Youz comin’ to see me Orgak?” She was covered head-to-toe in soot from a long day at the forge. Groff’s indentured servant. Thurgga had a singular purpose in life: make Groff armor. Of course her latest creations were better suited for the Dark Elf privies. But she was making good progress. Groff had dumped more plat into her than a thirsty dwarf in an Erudite tavern. Hopefully, it would pay off. 
<br />

<br />
“Youz seen Groff?” He asked, dismissing her invitation. 
<br />

<br />
“Not since him here a tenday ago ta gif me ore. Youz wanna see wut I made wit it?” She was pointing to the makeshift armory where the forge had just been installed.
<br />

<br />
Orgak knew better. Unless the hand of Innoruuk had reached down and guided her hand itself, it’d be a bent file or a lantern that wouldn’t hold oil. “No, go sell it to da bigguns and tell dem it’s art. Me’z tired.”
<br />

<br />
Groff shuffled through the cramped stone entry way of the cave he had staked out as his own in the crowded foriegn quarter of the Dark Elf city, grumbling softly to himself and rubbing his eyes with his free hand. Slung over his back were four large sacks hanging heavy with angular shapes poking into the sides of the fabric.
<br />

<br />
As his eyes readjusted to the dim light filtering through the oval room from the fires of the forge, he noticed Thurgga, staring at something in the shadows behind him, an odd look on her face. He shuffled a few feet farther toward her, his hand still to his face, then dropped the bags with a heavy clank and spun, struggling to free his lance from the sling on his back and throwing out his other hand toward the supposed attacker in the corner. Thurgga let out a sharp "Eeep!", reaching out with a look of horror on her face as Groff began mumbling the secret words Hukluk had taught him years ago in the confines of Night Keep. His hand began to take on an orangish glow and the air surrounding it wavered and bubbled with the heat and energy he called up. Thurgga turned pale, blanching in terror at the realization of what was about to happen. Suddenly, he swung his hand around and laid it on a rat scurrying across the work table behind him. The rodent gave up a long sharp squeal before collapsing in a simmering, smoking heap.
<br />

<br />
"Damn it, Orgak, yous make me kill Sparky. Hims last swamp rat Groff had frum home. Sneeky shammy hidin in shadows in sumbuddy home... Well, wez best eets dis befoar it gets cold."
<br />

<br />
Still pale, Thurgga remembered through the fog that Ogres indeed need to breathe, and she let out the stale air she'd been holding in for the last minute. Groff turned calmly and picked up the dropped bags, shoving them her way roughly as he tossed the now hoplessly entangled lance and sling into a corner and turned toward the cupboard for a loaf of bread to use with the now deceased Sparky.
<br />

<br />
"Ogur gurls gets to wurk, makes Groff armur, not plays wit Groff frends. Mebbe yous make sumthin gud dis time.... new sling fer da lance. Dis wun no gud."
<br />
Orgak’s amusement at the whole scene faded, realizing this was indeed tonight’s dinner. It was rat, cooked from the inside out by magic. It wasn’t gnome soufflé. It wasn’t pickled Erudite. It wasn’t even a skewered Froglok. The only thing worse tasting – if you could say it had a taste at all – was the bread he could summon with magic. His calloused hand absently touched the bracer on his right wrist. Years and years he had saved every cent come his way; to one day afford this single piece of armor. Now that he owned it, he was impoverished. 
<br />

<br />
Orgak’s growling stomach caught Groff and Thurgga’s attention. Groff turned to Orgak with an overly-concerned look. “You gonna kill more o’ dem big mean spiders so youz can sell thread? Orgak, deh spider killer!” He through up his hands in mock fear.
<br />

<br />
As though he heard none of this, Orgak snapped off the rat’s charred head and sucked its brains out from the base of its skull. Prepared correctly it was quite the troll delicacy, but this just tasted like burnt curdled milk. 
<br />

<br />
After an otherwise uneventful meal, Thurgga was back at the forge. Groff and Orgak proceeded to sharpen weapons, maintain armor, and do other Trollish things that are better left to the imagination.
<br />

<br />
CLANG – CLANG – CLANG – “OWOOOOH!” (She had smashed something painful by the sound of it.) Orgak looked to Groff, who only shrugged. 
<br />

<br />
Upon returning to his own cramped hole adjacent to the larger, but still cramped, hole the Shaman guild had been displaced to, Orgak saw a note nailed to his door. Apparently, the secret port of the pirates off the shores of Erudin had been found. With a dismissing grunt, he crumpled up the letter and tossed it into a corner as he ducked through the portal.
<br />
Groff snarled quietly to himself as he padded along the rough stone floors of the exiled Troll Shaman's Guild. 
<br />

<br />
"Stupid gurl, she break hand, break hammur. Cost Groff gud muneys fix. And fer whut? Dis."
<br />

<br />
He disgustedly held up before him a strange piece of metal working that could only be described as a failure of art and science. A barrel shape with an open bottom twisted away at an unhealthy angle and curved to close in at the top, where there were two irregularly sized holes. On one side another hole, larger than the two in the top listed off toward the front and on the other side two smaller holes were placed side by side horizontally.
<br />

<br />
"Whut she tinks, dat groff has too heds and three arms? Junk!"
<br />

<br />
Stomping heavily into Orgak's quarters, he dropped the mangled metal in a corner and slumped down heavily on a stone outcropping.
<br />

<br />
"Here, Orgak, Groff bring you 20pp leaky cookpot. Thurgga say it armur, but... well, yous sees."
<br />

<br />
Orgak looked up dispondantly from the empty plate he had been musing over just as both of their stomachs began a chorus of growling that made even a passing Dark Elf shudder in apprehension.
<br />

<br />
"Now wez got no fude, no muneys. Haff-tings in forust make Groff cough da hare-balls, stupid harey feetz... Hate dis place."
<br />

<br />
Orgak merely nodded, pensively eyeing a crumpled bit of paper in the corner.
<br />
Orgak wearily reached over where the crumpled note lay. He gave it a toss to Groff and then proceeded to fill his backpacks with his belongings that were strewn about his quarters. Groff shot him a curious glance and proceeded to peruse the note, turning it right side up after a few moments. 
<br />

<br />
“Wut youz tinkin? Fishin’ better dere?” 
<br />

<br />
“AAARGH! We’z gonna be pirates!” Orgak spun 180 degrees to face Groff in exaggerated enthusiasm. He had wrapped a piece of fabric over the right side of his head to cover an eye. It fell off before he finished the exclamation.
<br />

<br />
“Privates!? Why youz wanna be a private? Youz don’t like boats!” Groff was exasperated by the divergence from the problem at hand. 
<br />

<br />
“Where dere privates, dere’s treasure, right?” Orgak gave Groff a hopeful look.
<br />

<br />
Groff scrutinized his surroundings, giving more thought to the current living situation rather than the immediate vicinity. “Well, it ain’t here.” He spat on the ground and uttered a long string of curses, the word “inkies” was mentioned more than a few times.
<br />

<br />
Within a few minutes the pair was making their way to the exit of the city of Neriak, Thurgga in tow. Orgak regarded Thurgga questioningly. “takin’ her to deh Haven. Better forges dere anyway.” Groff informed him.
<br />

<br />
At the entrance to the passage that led into Neriak from the forest of Nektulos, a Dark Elf was showing a handful of trolls various moves with her lance. This was Flavaa, a Shadowknight just a few seasons younger in experience than Groff. She had always been kind to Orgak and Groff, which gave them hope that maybe all Dark Elves didn’t see the troll race as just another layer of meat between themselves and their light-skinned cousins. 
<br />

<br />
Upon noticing the pair exiting Neriak with all of their belongings, she turned to regard them and accidentally ran her lance completely through her sparring partner. The young troll fell to the ground doubled over, his hands trying to hold in his guts. His warder, little more than a baby alligator was licking the wound. Whether it was out of hunger or concern for it’s master, one couldn’t tell. Orgak said a quick prayer accompanied by some waving of his arms and the wounds disappeared. That situation handled, he turned his attention to Flavaa. 
<br />

<br />
“You Trolls headed somewhere?” She asked. 
<br />

<br />
Orgak started to do his “We’z gonna be pirates!” bit but was stopped short by a heavy swat to his back from Groff.
<br />
"Shhh... she still inky, Orgak," Groff wispered rather loudly. A slight raise of her eyebrows was the only response Flavaa gave to this comment.
<br />

<br />
"Err, wez go to Ogguk. Orgak auntie Murga der, she haff-Ogre, she look aftur da gurl. Biggur doars der two!" Groff covered with his most charming smile. A young Dark Elf necromancer passing them nearly fainted.
<br />

<br />
Orgak shoved his elbow in Groffs ribs as he stammered, "My auntie not haff-Ogre, she all Troll! Err... she jus go to Ogguk cuz... she like da smell, yah, da smell. Wez gotta go, Flavaa, yous teech dees yungins gud!"
<br />

<br />
The two Trolls shuffled quickly off into Nektulos forrest, dragging Thurgga behind them. As they made their way toward the river and the common lands beyond the forest, Orgak grumbled loudly, "Why you tell her me auntie a Ogre? Dat not nise. Mes not evun has a auntie Murga."
<br />

<br />
Groff threw up his hands at Orgak in frustration. 
<br />

<br />
"Cuz we not wants da inkies cum, make privates ded ur takes dem ovur. Wes get away from da inkies cuz we no likes dem. Dey find out bout da tresure, dey goes der fer shur. Gud ting me da smart wun, you roons evurting wit big mowth." As if on que, two Troll stomachs and an Ogre belly rumbled in chorus.
<br />

<br />
After making one last rude gesture to a patrolling Dark Elf guard – his back was turned -- on their way out of Nektulos, the trio moved on into the Commonlands. They had decided that they would treat themselves with a few flasks of the tasty water sold by the gnome just outside the Freeport gates. It had a minty flavor and a few flasks would last them until they reached their destination, wherever that may be. 
<br />

<br />
Carefully avoiding the inns and groups of guards that patrolled the Commonlands, they reached the point where the grass turns to trampled earth and stopped. Orgak began a long chant that rang all too familiar with Groff. “Youz goin’ ta lotsa trouble, just let me bash’em once.” 
<br />

<br />
As if not even hearing the protests, Orgak reached down and pet the translucent wolf that had appeared at his side. This was one of those guilty pleasures in which Trolls often indulged, the killing of fair-skinned guards. These two had turned it into a game, if the guard didn’t wet his breeches by they time it was over, it wasn’t considered a success.
<br />

<br />
The Freeport Militia felt it was part of their duty to rid the woodland area of its natural inhabitants, considering any creature great or small that came within their immediate vicinity to be a threat. This led to many rumors about the size of the Militiamen’s manhoods. Orgak sent the spirit wolf out to act as bait. The wolf, as incorrigible as his master, lept off, with as much of a smile that a wolf could express. 
<br />

<br />
“Halt! Foul Beast! You have incurred the wrath of the Freeport Militia!”
<br />

<br />
The wolf – “woofy” as Orgak often called him -- gave the guardsman a nip on the shin to get him going and then appeared to retreat to where the two Trolls and the Ogre lay in wait. Once woofy had him near the tree they were hiding behind, Orgak sprung out to face the guard. 
<br />

<br />
“BOOGABOOGABOOGA!” Orgak’s thumbs were in his ears, his tongue waggling about and his eyes were crossed. Slate was back on his heels, momentarily caught off guard. He forgot about the wolf he was chasing and pulled back his sword to take a mighty swing at the Troll. Before he could follow through and deal a blow of any sort to this foul Priest of Innoruk, he was upside down in the air held fast by Groff’s one hand that was gripping his ankles. 
<br />

<br />
“Gifs me dat before youz hurt sumboddy” Orgak reached and took the sword from the mortified Slate’s hand. Groff began to vigorously shake him and didn’t stop until the jingling from any coins in the purses lining his belts had ceased. When it was all said and done, they had a handful of plat, a helm emblazoned with the symbol of the Freeport Militia, and a short sword. 
<br />

<br />
As they padded into the tunnel running from the Eastern Commonlands toward the great Northern Desert of Ro, Groff nibbled voraciously at scrap of brown leather, gnawing off chunks and swallowing them with a satisfied 'Urp!'.
<br />

<br />
"Gud tinkin, get da pinky bootz. Dey not swamp rat, but bettur eetin dan de nasty blak bred." Orgak mumbled through a mouthfull of his own. "Wen yous put him in da crack in rock, make shure blud don' all fall out him, dat his nek don crack two much? Yous shure he gets out soon tho? Me hate ta spoil da fun nex time wez cum thru heer."
<br />

<br />
Groff nodded, "Yah, him uncomf...err... umcampfru.. him twistud all up and no feels gud, but not die... not yet. Not like littul haff-ting... " Groff growled, obviously upset. "Da nex time mez catch dat littul *#@*$*&&$#^@(+! mez gunna shows him how feel ta get whack in soft spots wit bunduls uf sticks!" he vowed, shaking his fist in the air at an imaginary Jimble Woodentoe.
<br />

<br />
Thurgga simply followed along silently munching on her scrap of Freeport Militia Boots, staring wide eyed at the world around her, her new "hat" hanging lopsided on her head, the Freeport Militia symbol scratched over with several Trollish obsceneties.
<br />

<br />
“Stupy dezert. Too hot. Makes me sticky.” Orgak was carrying his breastplate in his hand rather than wearing it. Sweat was running down his face and their pace had slowed considerably. Groff had killed a desert tarantula and run this lance through the carapace to make it into a parasol. After only a few steps, Thurgga was holding it over Groff’s head with Orgak making attempts to position himself under it for shade.
<br />

<br />
Once they reached the beach and were drawing close to where Northern Ro became the Oasis of Ro, they noticed a gathering of young adventurers. None of them were wearing anything special, most of them had fine steel short swords and poorly sewn leather tunics. It was too hot to really mess with them, so the Trolls proceeded to step over them, deliberately disturbing their camp. Trolls were not all that uncommon in this area, but the young warriors kept a watchful eye nonetheless. 
<br />

<br />
Thurgga waved at them and gave them a meek “ello pinkies” as she passed. One of them, a ranger by the looks of it, simply stated “Specs are out, watch your arse.” The ranger was apparently an out of body spirit – he was completely naked save some undergarments and looked a bit transparent. Thurgga’s eyes went wide and she turned to Groff. “Blah, stupy pinkies skeered of some ghosties. We bash dem if dey getz in our way.”
<br />

<br />
Upon coming to the docks, it was apparent that the Spectres had indeed been unleashed from their stone mount in the middle of the Oasis lake. Bodies were strung everywhere, one looking exactly like the ranger who had bade them warning. Orgak and Groff merely chuckled quietly as Thurgga looked upon the scores of corpses, eyes wide in disbelief. They had nearly reached the break in the stone walls that separated the Southern Desert of Ro from the Oasis when Orgak walked headlong into a giant foot, attached to a giant leg, that led upward to the rest of a giant body. Shouts of “KAZEL!” could be heard nearby.
<br />

<br />
As Orgak collided into the giant foot, Groff stopped short behind him, his breathing heavy and ragged from the long climb up the dune. Thurgga slammed into his back as he stopped, and dropped the lance and carapace parasol, knocking the Freeport Militia Helm off of her own head and making such a clanging racket as everything crashed down around her that the baleful shout was not at first audible to the three.
<br />

<br />
Groff scanned his eyes up from the impediment in Orgak's way to a huge and knobby knee, then gulped audibly, a look of sad resignedness washing over his face as he realized what was about to happen.
<br />

<br />
Reaching out, he grabbed Orgak, hauling him up and back in to Thurgga toward the gap in the Giant's legs and the narrow pass that lead to the Souther Desert of Ro.
<br />

<br />
"Run! Runrunrun! Feetz carry, yous go, GIT!" he shouted at them as he back pedalled before the Giant.
<br />

<br />
Cazel bent forward slightly to get a better look at the foolish creature causing such a commotion and disturbing his ponderous thoughts, placing an enourmous calloused hand on one knee and slipping a rather large "rapier" from his belt with the other hand. "Foolish little green infidel! You will pay dearly for disturbing the mighty Cazel!" he shouted.
<br />

<br />
Groff's eyes widened as the giant brandished a 10 foot long rapier in the air and stepped towards him. Struggling to think of a way out of the mess, he quickly murmured the spell that would make him take on the features of a dead creature, sneakily decieving enemies. The skill had saved him many an injury, and he had come to rely on the deception to get him out of very sticky situations. As he weaved his arms in and out and prepared to finish the casting, Groff took a half step back, bracing himself for the release of magical energies which would throw him to the ground and change his normally beautiful Troll features into a charnelhouse scene of ripped dead flesh. Having forgotten about the abandonned parasol, however, his foot struck not on the soft sand of the dunes but on the slick carapace, shooting his feet out from under him and planting him face first in the sand.
<br />

<br />
"Groff has fallen to the ground." Orgak whispered to Thurgga as they watched from the safety of the pass.
<br />

<br />
"Urghrupp," Groff murmured, struggling to right himself as the Giant's first blows landed on his back. "Dis jus not Groff's day." He regained his footing, managing to come up with his lance in his hand, and turned to face the angry Cazel, parrying what blows he could while trying to regain his composure for another casting.
<br />

<br />
"Azshnaz Gimba..HICK..Urrp..HICK!" Groff urped and hickuped as he attempted the second casting. "Dis def-HICK-nantly not Groff's day..." Coughing out a mouthful of dust and sand, he began again, only to miss a parry and be whacked soundly in the center of his forehead with the Giant's weapon.
<br />

<br />
"Lookit...da purty burdies...ohh" he mumbled before sliding down to his knees.
<br />
Seeing that the standard procedure of Groff’s pretending to die while they got out of range wasn’t going to work, Orgak spat on the ground and cursed. He cupped his groin and gave it a hoist, then hurriedly replaced his breastplate. He threw a handful of Peridots at Thurgga and shouted “Getz clerics!” 
<br />

<br />
Orgak knew they both were going to die, he had no Woofy, no enchantments, and Cazel was much more powerful than he. But he couldn’t just stand by and do nothing. Trying to get the monstrous being’s attention he threw his book of prayers at it. It hit him in the back of the knee, but he hardly noticed. Not sure what to do next he decided to see if he could bring Groff back into the game. Orgak threw a couple of quick healing spells his way. Most of the soon-to-be mortal wounds were closed up a bit, but new ones were appearing too fast for the shaman to keep up. 
<br />

<br />
There was only one way to draw Cazel’s attention from Groff, but what would he do after he had the giant’s attention? He cast a spell that caused the giant’s feet to grow roots and adhere him to the ground. Giants hate that. Orgak stepped up behind Cazel and bit him hard right in the behind. He spat out a chunk of the beast’s arse onto the dusty desert floor. The giant turned without so much as a pause and began to pummel him mercilessly. Orgak fell back hard, the wind shot out of him. But he crawled back to where the giant was trapped to the earth so that he wouldn’t turn back to Groff again. The blows came so fast and so hard, the priest couldn’t even get out two words of a prayer without having the breath knocked out of him. The only thing he could hope for was for Groff to come to soon enough to think of something better before the giant had finished off the both of them.
<br />

<br />
“YOU FUGGIN KILL STEALING TROLLS!!!! CAZEL IS OURS!!! WE WERE HERE FIRST!!!”
<br />

<br />
Suddenly, Orgak was up and on his feet. His stomach ached and his body screamed in pain as the cleric’s healing magic coursed through him. He was alive, but still being beaten on by an enraged and powerful giant. Then, the blows stopped. The giant was running off after a group of adventures who were calling to him like a dog, slapping the sides of their legs and clicking their tongues. A human in brilliant armor and a fiery sword stepped up to where Groff was sitting, trying to clear his head. 
<br />

<br />
“I should have let him kill you just for trying to take him from us. If you want him, take your turn. Next time, I’m reporting you! Stupid Trolls.”
<br />

<br />
Orgak sat down hard and watched the human, glowing with enchantments and waving his fiery sword, run off after the coveted Cazel.
<br />

<br />
Groff raised his severely battered head and murmered. "Whaa? We getz 'im?"
<br />

<br />
Orgak helped him to his feet and they struggled off toward the pass to South Ro where Thurgga waited, still dumbstruck with peridots scattered on the ground before her. Once Groff was situated into a more comfortable place than the underneath of a Giant's foot, Orgak sat and meditated on the beauty and perfection of hate, visualizing the arrogant pinky's face in several instances. Refreshed, he healed Groffs wounds and his own.
<br />

<br />
Smacking Thurgga to break her out of the state of shock she was in, Groff turned to Orgak. "Nex time, wes jus take boat to ovurder, stay wit da sarnies, wher it saif." 
<br />

<br />
As they squeezed through the narrow ravine in the rocks that surrounded the Oasis of Marr and protected it from the lands to the south, Groff began to smile. "Wez almost home!" he exclaimed happily. A rock smashed into the back of his helm sharply, making the enchanted metal ring.
<br />

<br />
"Wez no live der no mor, yous forgot? Da froggies take Grobb wen we wuz away, now dey got city locked up titur dan uh wud elf legs on tree-city festivul nite...err...much titur dan dat!"
<br />

<br />
Groff let out a string of curses that made Thurgga blush and step back so quickly that she lost her footing, sliding down and out of the pass to the base of a huge sand dune, into a wood elf druid. She looked up and blushed even more at the shapely leather-clad legs stradling her midsection.
<br />

<br />
Groff and Orgak shimmied down and went to collect the wayward Ogre girl, eyeing the druid.
<br />

<br />
"Hail, wud elf. Sorry, gurl not two brite." Groff explained.
<br />

<br />
"AC is camped, Trolls. Move along, I don't like hill sitters." The woman replied. Groff considered her for a moment, then decided that she'd likely engrave something nasty on his and Orgak's tombstones. He picked Thurgga up, and with a nod they trudged up the hill and into the desert.
<br />

<br />
"Groff begin to reely hate da pinkys...." he muttered as they made their way past spiders, madmen and undead toward greener hills.
<br />

<br />
Their steps became a bit lighter as they exited the sandy wind-racked landscape of the Desert of Ro. The heat was less intense and the humidity was palpable, which was a bit closer to being a swampish climate, and that afforded some comfort to the harried trio. Finding it a bit easier to breathe, the Trolls began to revel in adventures past. Giants felled, tombs desecrated, and pinkies tormented. Thurgga’s eyes wide and intent on every broken syllable, she was tempting herself with thoughts of life away from a hot forge. 
<br />

<br />
During a breather on a hillside, they finished off the tasty leather boots – courtesy of the Freeport Militia. As Orgak turned to where the Bard, Andrad Filla, stood with an ever-present mean look, his demeanor changed noticeably. It wasn’t the unfriendly Filla that darkened his thoughts; it was the entrance to the Swamp that lay behind him. This was the unspoken reason they had traveled this path, to take in the sight of Grobb, now under control of the Frogloks. Surely they could have saved themselves the pain of seeing their glorious home, defiled by the blessed of Marr, by traversing the Planes, but it felt as though it was their duty to remind themselves of the overriding priority in every Troll’s life. 
<br />

<br />
In wordless unison, the group gathered their packs and turned to move toward the pass. They exchanged hateful looks with Filla, as they had done so many times in their youth. Groff made a rude gesture and muttered something about Filla’s mother being part Iksar and that was their exit from the Desert of Ro.
<br />

<br />
----------------------------------------------------------------
<br />

<br />
They stared solemnly, intently, at the guards stationed at the entrance to what now was called Gukta. Orgak had stopped momentarily at the stone hand that once been the haunt of the master of poison, Stragak. He said a quick prayer, vowing to avenge his death with the lives of as many of Marr’s chosen as he could end. He then caught up with Groff, who was squeezing the life out of a tad, its gore running through his fingers. And now the three stood together in unseen defiance of this new breed of Frogloks that had taken their home. 
<br />

<br />
Throughout a long period of silence, the Trolls were wrought with a flood of emotions, hate not being the least of them. Groff was teetering on his feet, the fire in his belly urging him onward to avenge this atrocity and reclaim his home, all the while his instincts holding him back as it would be certain death with little to no accomplishment. Finally resolving to live and fight another day he turned to Orgak, “We’z smashem, just not today.” And with that, they made their way to the land of the Ogres. 
<br />

<br />
As they stepped off of the mossy path leading from Innothule swamp to the dark swampy forest of the Feerott, Thurgga took a deep breath and her eyes brightened, a gruesome smile spreading across her flat, homely face. She paused for a moment to take in the sights, sounds and smells of a home she'd hardly known as Groff and Orgak paused to get their bearings. 
<br />

<br />
"Wez cood go ta da stone by Ogguk, but Groff owe sum muney ta da Bouncer Foog... mebbe be best ta cut crost da rivur by lizzy ayeland, go ta da spyurs in karana. da humies der mor forgivin dan Bouncer Foog wen yous owe him muneys."
<br />

<br />
Orgak nodded, flashing a glance to the enraptured Thurgga.
<br />

<br />
"Yah, der dat two. Lizzy ayeland it is."
<br />

<br />
Groff collected Thurgga and the three began to walk down the river bank, keeping the riverbound island in view. When they passed the fallen pillar that served as a bridge across to the Tae Ew's ancestral home, they slipped into the murky water and swam silently and quickly to the island's bank. Climbing out and making their way silently along the river's edge, Groff's ears were alert and his eyes bright and flashing. The inhabitants of this small hill were no match for he and Orgak, but they could quickly make a dead smith out of Thurgga. And dead smiths don't finish Blackened Darkscale Armor for Groff. As they cleared the pillars and trees and approached the northern tip of the tiny island, he motioned for Orgak and Thurgga to stay put, then silently crept up to take a closer look. He reached the top of the hill and paused, the sounds of battle becoming audible over the splashes of the water on the bank. A young Gnome was fighting one of the lizards who patrolled this end of the island, a pet skeleton clawing at the scaley back of the beast. The gnome looked a bit worse for the wear, but his black breastplate and red boots told Groff all he needed to know about the young one. He was a Shadow Knight, and was attempting to collect the ellusive Darkforge armor which had been lost centuries ago by failed knights of Cazic Thule. He himself had at one time quested for this prize, and had completed his set after many battles and injuries. He watched in silence for a while as the Gnome strained his meager skill to best his opponents. Orgak and Thurgga, tired of waiting with soggy feet at the base of the river, tromped up behind him.
<br />

<br />
"Dat dinnur, Groff?" Thurgga asked, licking her chops in anticipation.
<br />

<br />
Having helped Groff to find pieces of the decaying armor the Tae Ew hoarded as trophies of their victory over the "lesser" servants of Cazic, Orgak quickly shook his head. "No, Thurgga, dat not dinnur. Dat may be trubbel, but not dinnur."
<br />

<br />
As Orgak quietly explained the gnome's purpose here so far from his home in the stony Steamfont Mountains, Groff watched the young knight, enraptured by visions of his own quest. So distracted was he by the memories that he barely noticed in time as the young knight chased a Tae Ew Judicator under the influence of Cazic Thule's fearsome power directly into the path of a wandering Crusader. His master attacked, the Gnome's skeleton sqealled loudly and charged into battle, only to recieve a blistering bolt of energy directly to the chest, blowing the small reanimated creature into thousands of sharp fragments. The Gnome stopped at the sight of a new, fresh enemy, torn momentarily between the need to finish off his fleeing prey and the dread of exposing his back to such a powerful opponent. A moments hesitation was all it took for the fleeing Judicator to realize that he now had the upper hand, and he turned, beginning to cast healing magicks upon himself as the Crusader closed on the young knight.
<br />

<br />
With a roar, Groff leapt up from his place of concealment, startling Orgak and Thurgga almost as much as the combatants on the hill before them. He charged swiftly toward the Gnome, drawing his lance as he closed on the shocked youngster. Swiping only inches above the Gnome's head, Groff's lance crashed into the spellweaving Justicar, splattering himself and the remaining Tae Ew with thick brown blood, and drenching the Gnome in brain matter and gore. Taken aback by such a viscious attack, the Crusader paused to consider his options. He didn't have a chance to finish his thoughts as Groff streched out an orange glowing hand and placed it almost gently upon the snout of the lizard-man. A horrible rending sound rose up from inside the creature as its scaley skin expanded rapidly as if it had just been boiled from within. When it finally fell to the mossy ground, steam rose up from eye sockets, nostrils and mouth, and the beast's forked tongue was swollen and blackened. Groff looked down at the Gnome huddled at his feet, the rage of battle receding from his features slowly. "Gud armur on dat wun, yung nite. Take, and remembur name, Groff Gorespiller. Him save yur life today, sumday yous repay da favur."
<br />

<br />
The dumbstruck Gnome only nodded, then proceeded to wet his greaves, nearly falling back from terror and exhaustion. Groff turned back to Orgak and Thurgga, smiling as he waved them on across the island and to the other bank of the river.
<br />

<br />
"Yous get such a kick outta dat... show off," Orgak muttered to Groff as they swam across and found the trail that would lead them to the Rathe Mountains.
<br />

<br />
Groff chuckled quietly.<br />_________________<br />65 Troll Shaman 
<br />
