			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Groff took in the change of scenery with a long sigh.  "Hatez deh walkin.  We'z needz hors er sumtin."  He turned a curious glance behind him after hearing a startled "Eeep!" from Thurgga.  Orgak was rummaging through her satchels and was about to lift up the back of her tunic.  "Wut youz doin Orgak?  Dis iz not deh time fer dat."  Orgak snapped-to and straightened himself.  "Oh, sorry, misclick."  Thurgga was blushing profusely, but did not seem completely unhappy about what had just happened.  Groff rolled his eyes and muttered something about springtime.  
<br />

<br />
The earthen walls of Rathe Mountains reached up around them, casting a shadow on their damp well-trodden path.  The thunderous footsteps of hill giants could be heard in the distance with shouts of "CAMPED!" and "KSER!" following behind.  Groff had a particular hatred for this area.  Lots of "pinkies" and just as many ways to get lost on the way to Lake Rathetear.    
<br />

<br />
"Youz gotz da map, Groff?"  Orgak was trying not to notice Thurgga edging nearer ever so slowly.  Groff looked up and off to the walls of the path, patting his belly.  "Youz ate da map?"  Groff winced noticeably and turned to walk on.  "Me'z know da way.  You'z just keep up."  Thurgga bounded after him so as not to be left behind.
<br />

<br />
After finally admitting being lost and exchanging colorful metaphors with each other, Orgak stopped in his tracks, nose in the air.  He inhaled deeply.  Groff did the same.  Something spectacular was in the air.  It was the distinct smell of "MEAT!" they both shouted at once.  On the rise up ahead was a small camp of humans with a fire standing out against the falling sun.  
<br />

<br />
In all their lumbering for the bandit camp, a man stood and bore his rapier.  "Back Trolls!  WE are ruining these lands, now get lost!"  Those were his last words... which ended in a gurgle as Groff's fist met his throat.  Four dead bandits and a three full bellies later, two Trolls and an Ogre were lying on the ground, looking up at the stars with content smiles on their faces.  
<br />

<br />
"Eh hem!" Came a voice from Orgak's immediate left.  The food-laden Troll was on his feat with much effort.  "Groff... dis woofy iz talkin'"  He was staring at a wolf that was much like any other wolf except that it was almost transparent and had the hint of a smirk on it's face.  
<br />

<br />
The spirit heaved a sigh.  "Did you take this person's life, shaman?"  
<br />

<br />
Orgak replied "Dis wun wuz Groff's." He pointed to another corpse in the camp and then another. "Dat wun and dat wun wer mine."  
<br />

<br />
Thurgga was wildly flipping through the pages of a tome that none of them would dare eat.  All it said on the cover was "Allakhazam."  She found whatever she was looking for and pointed it out to Groff.  He quickly jumped in "No Orgak, youz killed dat wun.  Yeah, dat wun."  He shot Orgak a pleading stare.  
<br />

<br />
Orgak shrugged.  "Groff right, woofy, dat wun iz mine."  The wolf rolled it's eyes and lowered it's head so that the top of it touched the ground, hard.  It did this repeatedly, muttering something about Trolls.  Finally it looked back up at Orgak, this time with a look of impatience.  "Okay, fine... WARING" the word was drawn out and reeked of sarcasm. He hurried through the rest of the words as though he had said them a thousand times.  "Take this to where the humans gather to spoil the land and water. Some call it a port. There you will find one of us, a shaman like yourself. Give him the gem and perhaps he will tell you more of the spirits. Here's your gem.  I'm done."  
<br />

<br />
The spirit uttered a curse that made Thurgga turn red and turn her eyes to the ground and was gone in an instant.  
<br />

<br />
Orgak contemplated the gem and shrugged.  "We'z not goin to pinky city!"  He tossed the gem over his shoulder and waved his hand in the air dismissingly.  
<br />

<br />
"Stupy talkin woofies."<br />_________________<br />65 Troll Shaman 
