			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The trio made short work of leftover Orc provisions, then packed up their meager gear and began walking toward the water’s edge.  Eying the lapping lake surface uncertainly, Groff slipped a clawed foot out of his steel boots and dipped a toe into the clear lake water.  Shuddering, he let out a low growl.
<br />

<br />
”Dis not doo, Groff no like.  Wez find a bote an git across dat way.”
<br />

<br />
Orgak nodded, eyeing the water with every bit as much suspicion as his companion.  They walked on a bit down the shore, Thurgga grunting under the weight of the trio’s “luggage” which seemed to grow with each step they took.  Trolls rarely throw anything away, and find “treasures” in the most revolting of refuse piles.  Before the sun had crested it’s zenith, they came upon a small dugout canoe beached on the rocky bank.  Groff grinned from ear to ear, an expression that startled an overhead bird so severely that it missed a beat and nearly plummeted to the ground, releasing it’s partially digested breakfast as it struggled to recover.  The goey white and black mess fell through the crystal clear morning air, plopping soggily on the top of Orgak’s stubbled head.  Looking up in puzzlement, he raised a hand to his scalp, bringing it back down to sniff apprehensively at the stuff, then popped a wart bejeweled finger into his mouth, frowning. 
<br />

<br />
”Nah, no gud.” He mused, smacking his tongue against his lips.
<br />

<br />
”Whut yous meen no gud?  Dis wurk, gurl jus has ta swim.” Groff argued.
<br />

<br />
Orgak looked a bit confused for a moment, then his eyes wandered to the boat and ne nodded appreciatively.  “Dat ok.”
<br />

<br />
Thurgga struggled up, dropping her bundles with a clatter as the Trolls discussed the logistics of moving the boat across the vast lake.
<br />

<br />
”Gurl, yous pak da stuff in dere, den start swimmin’, long way cross da layk.”  Groff ordered.
<br />

<br />
”But, but, but…”
<br />

<br />
“No, swimmin’ no sound like dat.  It ‘splishy-splashy-sploshy’.” Orgak offered.
<br />

<br />
”Mez don’t swim.  Yous nebber lets mez, say ‘Gurl make armur, no ‘splishy’, only ‘clang’.” The Ogress pleaded.
<br />

<br />
Groff sighed heavily, rolling his eyes as he turned to Orgak. “Fine.  Orgak splishy, gurl an Groff rides bote.”
<br />

<br />
”Orgak only doggy paddul” The Shaman replied, grinning from ear to ear and shrugging his shoulders helplessly.
<br />

<br />
With an exasperated curse, Groff began stripping out of his armor, tossing it at the Ogre girl and mumbling curses under his breath.  Before long, he was down to his soiled leather breach-cloth, and the little canoe was nearly sunk under the weight of an Ogre, a Troll and four heavy haversacks full of gear. Gingerly slipping one foot into the water, Groff winced, but he set his face with determination and submerged himself slowly until only his head was bobbing above the surface.  Orgak cuckled softly as he and Thurgga ineptly paddled the small boat out into the water behind Groff, heading North toward the Plains of Karana.  
<br />

<br />
As heavy as the little boat was, paddling was difficult, sweaty work, and the duo made slow progress across the glassy surface.  Having fallen off of many a boat in a drunken stupor induced by OT outpost keggers, however, Groff’s swimming had become very good (especially when sober) and so he quickly outpaced his companions.  Before long, he had put so much distance between them that he could barely hear the labored grunts of the two paddlers and he calmly swam in the still morning water.  His mind began to wander in this quiet peace to other things until he suddenly heard a surprised exclamation from far behind him.  Spinning around, he expected to see some great monster from the deeps coming up to swallow his friends and their boat whole, but instead, Orgak was standing, waiving his arms wildly in the air and shouting happily, while Thurgga clutched the sides of the dugout fiercely, trying to keep them from tipping over.  With another curse, Groff began to swim back to them.
<br />

<br />
”Whut yous make so much noize fur?  Yous wakes up sumtin nasty if youz no shuts up.” Groff complained.
<br />

<br />
”Luk!  Fisshy!  Jus flote up to mez, rite to da bote!  Our luckee day!” Orgak exclaimed, waiving a dead fish in front of Groff’s bobbing nose.
<br />

<br />
”Smell kinda funny…” Groff replied, uneasily.  Nothing was ever this simple, and the Troll had long ago learned to beware sudden unexpected fortune.  As he tread water puzzling over the fish, Orgak exclaimed again, jumping up and down and nearly tossing the (by now, green) Ogre girl over the side with his commotion.
<br />

<br />
”Mor Fisshy!  Luk!  Dey comin up evurwayr!  Lots o’ fisshy!” He laughed, hastily grabbing up an empty sack from the pile of gear in the middle of the boat and stuffing it with as many dead fish as he could grab.
<br />

<br />
A puzzled look washed across Groff’s face as he treaded water, spinning around to look confusedly at the water around him.  Fish were now shooting up to the surface in incredible numbers, their eyes bloated and bulging.  As he pondered the strange phenomenon, his stomach growled.  Scrunching his face, he grunted.  A string of bubbles rose quickly to the surface of the water and broke, releasing a horrible stench over the water, and dozens of fish rose to the surface in a circle around him.  His eyes widened and a smile slowly spread over his face.  He scrunched up again and released another stream of bubbles.  The surface of the water quickly filled completely with floating fish, along with a few dead aqua goblins.  Groff began to laugh maniacally.
<br />

<br />
”Wez nebber be hungry ‘gain!” he exclaimed.  No sooner had the words left his mouth than a flash of light dazzled the trio, a gnome in a yellow robe stepping out of the rapidly closing portal with a stern look on his face.
<br />

<br />
”You Trolls should not be doing this.  You are exploiting, and this is your ONE AND ONLY warning!  Leave the area immediately and do not let us catch you doing this again!” the gnome boomed, his voice stunning and resplendant.  Groff and Orgak both began to rub at their eyes in disbelief.  
<br />

<br />
”Wha???  Wez no eggsplayding…err… well, not sur wut dat meens, mebbe wez iz…” Groff stammered.
<br />

<br />
”Yah, sorry pinky flashy tingie.  We’z jus cleens up deez fisshies, den we’s be movin’ along…” Orgak said, thinking quickly of his stomach.
<br />

<br />
“Your ill-gotten gains will be recalled.  Move along immediately.”
<br />

<br />
Cursing softly, Groff gave a shrug which almost upset his balance, then turned dejectedly and began swimming once again toward the far bank, Orgak and the Ogre girl in tow.  They reached the bank under the stern supervision of the floating gnome, then, with one last look at the lake and it’s seemingly endless bounty, they crossed over from the hilly region into the Plains of Karana, home of all manner of pinkies.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=348308">Groff Gorespiller</a>
<br />
Troll Dread Lord
<br />
