			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">GURGLE-GURGLE-GROOOOWLLL… Groff’s stomach churned and complained.  Several gnolls glanced at each other anxiously, wishing they were invisible.  Orgak was still licking his fingers hoping that the fish taste was still resident.  It wasn’t.    
<br />

<br />
The homes in the trees were elaborate perches for the bipedal fowl that strutted throughout this area.  They were fairly adept fighters, but weren’t ones to hold grudges.  Their eyes had the spark of sentience, but they seemed dense as to what two Trolls and an Ogre might be up to as they started a fire and fashioned a spit right at the base of one of the trees.  Satisfied with his craftsmanship, Orgak stood and wiped his hands on Thurgga’s tunic, soiling them all the more.  
<br />

<br />
“Wut we’z gonna eat?”  The young Ogress tried not to look at the Spirocs who were fluttering about the tree tops and pecking at the ground around them.  
<br />

<br />
Groff turned to her incredulously.  “Youz dummer dan me tawt, gurl.”  Her eyes welled up and her bottom lip was trembling.  She obviously had grown fond of the birds.  She always did have a soft heart, even in spite of being on the brink of starvation.  
<br />

<br />
Orgak caught on to her anxiety and felt that he should do his best to ease her concern.  He put his fists to his sides, flapping his arms like wings while strutting.  He was bobbing his head and wore a big toothy grin. “We’z feel like chikun tonite! Chikun toNITE!”   Needless, to say, this didn’t help.  Troll laughter ensued.
<br />

<br />
After a debate over whether a visit to Split Paw was in order (Orgak was looking to complete his suit of armor), they moved on toward the large stone bridge that would take them to the Scion and ultimately, the moon.  It was a quiet stroll, save for the long sighs which the Spiroc thrown over Groff’s shoulder drew out of Thurgga.  
<br />

<br />
Orgak was suddenly animated, eyes alight with excitement.  Groff drew his lips back, exposing his teeth and inhaled deeply.  Sure that something unpleasant was about to happen.  “Meh told youz ta eat slow.  Now youz make deh gurl sick. Go ofer by tree er sumtin.”  
<br />

<br />
“No no no, it not dat.  Look!” He pointed to the east, and right at a magnificent white horse, carried through the air on feathered wings.  “Horsy!  Wit wings!”  
<br />

<br />
“For extra protection?” Thurgga said quietly.  Grinning to herself.  The Trolls looked her way, confused, and then were back to gawking at the Pegasus.
<br />

<br />
“Meh wuntz it!”  Before there was time to argue, Orgak was off in a bound.  Thurgga, sure he meant to eat it reached out after him, pleading weakly.  A few magical words and Orgak’s feet were moving with the speed of a wolf.  Before the Pegasus noticed the Troll galloping towards it, big cheesey grin on his face, Orgak had its tail in his grip.  The Pegasus let out a whinney and its eyes were wild and frightened.  It darted through the air, dragging Orgak along with it, holding on with all the strength he could summon into his grip. 
<br />

<br />
“Whoah horsy!  Who-oh-oh-oh-ow!” He was bouncing along the ground, over rocks and mounds.  Battered, but still holding on, Orgak was trying to recite a spell to still the beast.  “No-bad-ow-horsy-ow-oh-AWK!”  Orgak was now stuck in a tree, still gripping the tail of the creature.  It turned back and bit his hand hard.  “OW!  STUPY!”  Orgak lost his grip, and the winged magestic horse, raced off into the distance.  
<br />

<br />

<br />
Back on the trail, toward the bridge, the group was quiet.  Orgak was rubbing sore spots from where he had been dashed against the ground in his pursuit of the Pegasus.  Groff halted them and nodded ahead.  “Pinkies on teh bridge.  Getz ready.”  
<br />

<br />
The militiamen guarding the bridge were serious about their work.  They did not suffer Trolls or Ogres passage.  The river was too wild for swimming (no one had ever made it across, though it looked calm and peaceful).  Orgak made quick work of memorizing the appropriate spells.  The idea was simple: run through invisible.  Groff popped out of sight in a blink.  Thurrga looked around for where he had gone.  Orgak said a few words and then the Ogress was invisible as well.  
<br />

<br />
“EEE!  Ware me at!?!”  This was her first time being invisible.  
<br />

<br />
“Shut up, gurl. Just run fer deh spirez and we’z  meet youz dere.”  There was a rustling of weeds and tall grass as she scampered.  Her path wove this way and that and finally ended abruptly at a tree.
<br />

<br />
“owweee”  She tried to stifle her yelp of fear and pain.  The Trolls were already at the base of the bridge, ready to cross.
<br />

<br />
“Shut up gurl!” Groff said lowly but frantically.  “Jus you runz to utter side.”  A few more moments passed, and there was a SPLASH! from just under the bridge.  Thurgga had fallen into the water.  
<br />

<br />
“RAH! STOOPID GURL!”  Groff had caught the guard’s attention with his angry words.  One of them was walking to where the Trolls stood.  Groff grabbed Orgak and hauled him over the side.  Groff’s entry into the water made a fountain.  Orgak met the ground hard, just shy of where the water began.  THUMP “#$!@”
<br />

<br />
They had narrowly avoided the guard and were huddled under the bridge.  They took the time to rest and assess their bodily damage.  Orgak was able to heal the cuts and bruises, but could do nothing for Thurgga’s shaken state.  She sat looking herself over, assuring herself that all her parts were there and could be seen.  Overhead, there was the sound of hooves meeting the stone of the bridge.  Groff gave Orgak a curious look and then pulled himself up the side of the bridge so that his head was visible to the passersby.  
<br />

<br />
“Who’z dat trip-trappin’ over our bridge?”  Groff said as Orgak’s head appeared alongside the other Troll’s.  Three goats gave them startled looks.  
<br />

<br />
“Lunch is wut be trippin’ trappin’!”  And so, our Trolls had won themselves another meal.
<br />

<br />

<br />
After some reassurance, Thurgga was the first to cross over the bridge and into the circle of spires.  Each received a gem from the scion, who blanched when Groff said “Journey to Luclin youz stupy pinky.”  
<br />

<br />
She made a rude gesture. “1 minute until port.  Gee I hope the guards don’t come this way.”  Fortunately, they did not.  Shortly thereafter, the trio had left Antonica and found themselves in the Nexus on the moon known as Luclin.<br />_________________<br />65 Troll Shaman 
