			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The din of the bazaar muted out anything comprehensible.  Groff's satisfaction from having thoroughly mortified Thurgga was washed away by the rush of the cacophony and was replaced by a scowl.  Orgak saw his mouth move as he said something... "Whatchoo sayin?"  
<br />

<br />
Groff attempted to penetrate the noise of the crowd by raising his voice.  Orgak shrugged, not hearing.  Groff put his mouth right to Orgak's ear and cupped his hands around the area to cut out the interference.  "NOIZE.  HATE NOIZE.  CAN'T STAND NOIZE!"  
<br />

<br />
"OOW!"  Orgak swatted Groff away and put a hand over his hear.  Thurgga was absorbing the sensory overload that was the Bazaar.  Casinos, buyers, and sellers were bartering and arguing.  Unworldly gems and armors hung from nearly every stall and platinum was flowing like a river.  A paladin in bright armor from another plane of existence held his hand out to her for a donation.  Always the soft heart, the Ogress reached for her coin purse and started to work with the string to open it.  Groff gave her a hard smack on the butt and shot a scowl to the Paladin.  The dwarf offered a conceding shrug and a wink.  
<br />

<br />
"Himz got more munniez dan us, stoopid gurl!  Gifs me dat purse bafore you gifs it all away to da twinkiez."  
<br />

<br />
Orgak was peering through the stalls looking for something.  His eyes landed on what he sought and he began rubbing his hands together and grinning.  "We'z go seez dah foorhead gurl.  See wutz she sold fer us."  Groff nodded in approval and yanked at Thurgga's arm.  
<br />

<br />
After laying low a few would-be auctioneers who approached them on their way to a stall near the back of the trader area, they paused and ogled at what they saw.  A young and hardly-clad Erudite was straightening her wares which were present in her booth.  Not even realizing what he was doing, Groff's hand reached out toward a blazing cloak that was hanging proudly at the front of the array.  His hand opened and closed, grasping at it from a distance, like a baby reaching for a pacifier but lacking the ability to speak.  His eyes were wide and transfixed.  His mouth was moving of it's own accord.  Orgak could just make out the words "Preciousssss... my preciousssss... "  
<br />

<br />
The shattering pain of a sap batting his hand away snapped him back to reality.  He howled and glared at the young valuptuous Erudite who answered him with a sneer "Only seventy thousand platinum and the cloak can be yours.  Otherwise, HANDS OFF!"  Groff's chest sank as he backed away a few feet.  
<br />

<br />
"We'z no wunt youz stupy cloak, Faera." Orgak stepped in front of Groff.  "Me'z wunt deh munniez frum all dat stuff youz sellin for me."  
<br />

<br />
The Erudite merchant threw her head back and laughed hard. (The weight of it causing her to nearly lose her balance.)  "Ah yes.  The Troll with the silks.  Very well then Shaman, here is your money, minus my commission of course."  The corners of Orgak's mouth dropped nearly below his chin as she placed a few silver pieces in his green gnarled hand.  
<br />

<br />
His frown turned to a snarl.  "Youz cheated meh!  I gifs you lots of gud stuff!"  
<br />

<br />
Faera snorted and then ducked in behind the curtain at the back of her stall.  When she reappeared a barbarian with an enormous axe strapped to his back stepped out and regarded Orgak menacingly.  He drew a deep breath and shouted above the roar of the Bazaar, "PRICE CHECK ON A RUSTY SHORT SWORD!"  The bazaar erupted with laughter.  Calls of "NOOB!" and "VENDOR TRASH" erupted from unseen patrons.  A nearby young Shaman poked his head around the side of the neighboring stall, "I can use them for pet weapons."
<br />

<br />
Faera chortled and then regarded the pair with an look of sympathy.  "Oh come on Trolls.  It's not so bad.  If you were to collect oh.. say... 40,000 more spider silks you could afford a decent upgrade to that gnoll skin you're so proud of."  
<br />

<br />
Orgak was no longer humbled, but agitated.  He narrowed his eyes and spoke menacingly at the Eruditess.  "I gifs you dis job.  Youz was enter.. enterta... gah!  Youz was dancin fer dorfs when me found youz!  Youz shood share some of dis stuff!"  
<br />

<br />
Groff stepped up beside Orgak and demanded "ya!  Ware youz get dis stuff ennyway?  Dis expensuf!"  He fondly fondled the cloak that was glowing red and warm to the touch.  
<br />

<br />
No sooner had Faera drawn a breath to answer when yet another incredibly muscular Barbarian pushed the Trolls out of his way and presented to her a tunic that was filthy with moss and mold.  "Forty thousand m'lady, just as you said."  She traced his granite jaw admiringly with her fingertips.  "Excellent work Vaynard.  You have proven your negotiating prowess once again."  She gave him a suggestive wink and then turned to regard the Trolls once more.  "As for you two.  You should leave now before I am forced to have you displaced.  You are frightening the customers away."  
<br />

<br />
The Barbarians formed a wall of muscle in front of Faera and threatened Groff and Orgak by reaching for the axes on their backs.  As the two monstrous warriors began making their way toward the trio (Thurgga had already backed away quite a bit) an "Eeep!" came from behind them.  This distracted the Barbarians so that they turned to find the source of the sound.  Groff took the opportunity to loose his polearm and have it ready for when they turned back around.  Orgak readied a spell for the encounter.  The musclebound bodyguards began backing away and parted so that the Trolls could see what was taking place in the back of the stall.  
<br />

<br />
"I think you should show these two generous Trolls some respect, forehead!  It seems as though you owe them a finders fee and now a keepers fee!  Because only their words will KEEP me from slicing your scrawny brown neck!"  
<br />

<br />
"Flavaa!" Groff cried out in astonishment. "Flavaa?  Wut youz doin here?"  Astonishment turned to confusion.
<br />

<br />
"I knew you boys would find trouble eventually.  I almost stepped in when Cazel took a liking to you, but I knew you could handle yourselves."  She grinned knowingly.  
<br />

<br />
"Youz mean youz been wit us deh whole time?" Groff said disbelievingly.  
<br />

<br />
"Yesh!" The Dark Elf exclaimed with a wide smile and then nodded to Thurgga.  Thurgga blushed profusely and gave her a little wave.  
<br />

<br />
"YOU KNEW TIS?!?  YOUZ KNEW DAT EH INKY WAS FOLLWIN US AN YOUZ SAY NUTTIN?"  Groff was in a rage, masking his embarrasment.  
<br />

<br />
"Easy now, Trolly boy.  She told me what you were up to and I figured you could use a hand.  I always did want to see a boat that didn't get stuck halfway to where you were going and Dulak sounds like a real adventure.  Don't worry, no one else knows... well.. except a bard, a cleric, a paladin, and a beastlord... but we can cover that later."  She laughed to herself and then brought the edge of her dagger closer to Faera's throat, remembering the task at hand.  
<br />

<br />
After some aggressive negotiations, Groff and Orgak had found themselves a new business partner... a reluctant one, but a partner nonetheless.  For once, Groff left the bazaar with a smile.<br />_________________<br />65 Troll Shaman 
<br />
LFHC (Looking for Home City)
