				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Walking up the stairs from the Bazaar to the rest of Shadow Haven, Groff's step was light and a broad, gruesome grin split his warty face from ear to ear.  He almost felt like whistling.  
<br />

<br />
"Come along, gurl, wez find you playse ta hammur," He said over his shoulder to the Ogress following him out of the din and clamor of the crowded market.  Groff raised his head and sniffed the air curiously, thinking he could likely find suitable lodgings by smell alone, but much to his dismay, the odor of rot was nearly inexistant.  With a "humph?!" and a shrug, he padded along the alleys and paths, sticking his head into windows as doors as he went.
<br />

<br />
Finally coming across a small Inn just across the way from the Warriors Arena, he stepped in, ducking to sidle through the small door, and placed himself in front of the service window.  "Mez wunt rume fer gurl.  She no needs much, unused closet be enuff," He said to the Innkeeper, his face scrunched up into what most folks would never identify as a "poker face".
<br />

<br />
"I don't serve your kind, Smelly Butt!" the Innkeeper snarled with a glare. 
<br />

<br />
With a snort, Groff wiggled back out of the Inn and began his search again.  Many hours (and blistered toes) later, he slumped down against a wall with a grunt.  "*&$#%*&! Stupy gurl, stupy pinkies.  Wut mez do now?  No can take her wit us, no send hur bak..." he growled to himself, Thurgga standing next to him, her eyes nearly filled to brimming with moisture, bottom lip trembling at the rejection and thought of being left alone and helpless in a strange city so far from the life she had known on Norrath.
<br />

<br />
Tapping his head against the wall in frustration while he attempted to think of a solution, suddenly, a small wooden sign hanging above a narrow stair across the path caught his eye.  With a sigh, he hauled himself to his feet, growled at the Ogress and started plodding toward the stairwell.  
<br />

<br />
The hall was narrow, and littered with refuse in a manner that seemed incongruous with the normally spotless city. Momentarily, the pair found themselves in front of a plain, shabby wooden door with a small sigil carved into it: a small bed imprinted on a coin.  "Yous best be on yer gud-est behav...err..bayhoov..err...  Yous acts nyce, else yous find yur own playse ta sleeps," Groff growled to the girl.  She nodded, her eyes widening and the volume of salty moisture in her eyes increasing.
<br />

<br />
Throwing the door open, Groff barged in quickly, attempting to seem imposing to whomever might be inside the building, but his weapon's hilt hung on the door frame, tangling him so badly that he nearly threw himself head first into the floor with his momentum.
<br />

<br />
Righting himself, he declared loudly, in no specific direction, "I wunt rume fer gurl.  I giv's yous too silvur...err...uh...munth!  Dat mez finul ansur!"
<br />

<br />
A lone Human crouched above an open fire, heating a can of what appeared to be some sort of beans.  He looked up at the pair with a grimace that might have scared Groff himself, had the Troll not been in such a foul mood.
<br />

<br />
"I don't bunk down with Trolls, Stinky.  Get out. Now." the Human replied.
<br />

<br />
Thurgga turned toward the door, sure that she was now homeless and helpless, soft sobs already starting to shake her enormous frame.  Groff simply stared at the Human, his black eyes seeming to glaze over frostily as his scowl turned downright nasty.  His hand squeezed and stroked the hilt of one of his smaller weapons, making the wood and leather creak, while the sound of his grating teeth might have convinced a passer-by that the entire building was about to collapse.
<br />

<br />
Very softly, he spoke.  "She not Troll, pinky. She ogur.  An she stay heer.  An if'n mez come bak, find out yous no treets hur gud, find out yous hurts hur, or makes hur cries, mes gunna rip all da pointy parts uv yous off, den stuff dem insides da insides parts, grind it all up and makes sumtin yummy outta it.  Den mez gets nasty.  Yous undurstands?"
<br />

<br />
Thurgga whirled around at Groff's words, her jaw dropping in amazement.  A wide grin spread across her face as she looked from the Troll to the cornered human and back.  Tears streamed down her face, making dirty rivulets.
<br />

<br />
"Yeah?  You think so, Ugly?  Well, I don't sit too well in overstuffed stomachs.  You want to carve off a piece, then come and get it!" the Human spat back as he brandished a crude knife and pulled a flaming log from his fire.
<br />

<br />
Groff eyed the fire momentarily, then a malicious glint flickered in his eyes as he turned his back to the Human and began to lower his greaves, bending over to expose a filty Trollish backside.  "Yous want play wit fiyur, pinky, yous gunna gets burn'd."  Scrunching up his face and grunting hard, a cavernous growl sounded from Groff's midsection.
<br />

<br />
After a split second's consideration, the Human dropped the torch and his knife and sidled quickly out of the corner, his hands in the air.
<br />

<br />
"Wait, wait, you win. You win!  Hold your fire, please!  This place is all I have, I don't want to see you bring it down on both our heads!" he pleaded, exasperatedly.
<br />

<br />
With a nod, Groff raised his greaves and turned to give the Human another menacing look.  "Yous remembur, I finds out yous no gud, no remembur da deel, I come back, yous no like!" he warned, flinging a handful of gold toward the man. "Dat enuff fer uh wiyul.  Brings bak mor laytur."
<br />

<br />
He turned toward the door and was met with a face full of Ogre cleavage as the overjoyed girl threw her arms around him and squeezed him in an enormous hug, blubbering something he couldn't quite hear with her meaty arms covering his ears.
<br />

<br />
"HMMMmmmffffphhhssss!  Grrruuuuuummmmmphhhbbbbrrrrrphhhtth!" he gasped.
<br />

<br />
Pushing him away long enough to hear his words, Thurgga beamed at the Troll. "Whut yous say, Groff, me hero?"    Her eyes twinkled moistly as she gave him an overstated wink.  "Yous tell mez in mornin'.  Wez get some 'rest' now!" she said in what she thought was a sultry, seductive voice.  The human grimaced as he retrieved the coins from the stone floor.
<br />

<br />
Groff eyed the girl with confusion for a moment.  Then, as the gravity of the situation slowly sunk in, his jaw dropped.  "Err... umm.... Mez has to...errr... ummm... Wez gots early start.....annnd...errr...ummm... Hasta go, now, Mez sees you laytur, buy bye!" he stammered as he tried to hastily slip out the door.  Not one to let her quarry slip through her...fingers, as it were, Thurgga grappled with the Troll, squeezing here, pinching there in what some scholars might consider to be a primative and disgusting Ogre mating ritual.  The human, desperately trying not to pay attention to the display, none the less had lost his appetite and sourly poured the now cooked beans into a clay pot he used as a bed pan.  "Blegh!" he muttered.
<br />

<br />
Only Groff's years of martial training and the magical properties of his armor allowed him to disengage himself from the hulking Ogress, and even these skills allowed him only a moment's opportunity for escape.  Rolling out of the door and into the narrow hall, he pushed himself to his feet and bolted up the stairs at a dead run, a lathered and eager Ogre right behind him.  Groff zig-zagged through the winding alleyways, knocking over barrels and crates as he went, sometimes ducking into a building only to exit by means of a window on the otherside.  The chase went on for over an hour before he finally made a last dash for the stairs leading to the Bazaar and the anonymity of a vast crowd of merchants and shoppers.  Weaving his way through the crowd, he turned to look over his shoulder and spotted the girl standing at the top of the stairs, searching the sea of heads for her quarry.  
<br />

<br />
Groff ducked and wove furiously, finally making his way back to the Erudite's stall, where Orgak was gleefully "reading" over the books, running a warted, dirty finger down the income column and giggling madly.  Groff slid to a stop beside his friend, ducking down and pulling some of the sheer curtains which adorned the stall around him in an attempt to hide.
<br />

<br />
"Wez gotta go, now!" He said urgently, just soft enough to be heard over the rumbling noise of the crowd.  Orgak threw an amused glance Groff's way. "Why?  Mez like dis playse.  Muniez!  Itza gas!" he sang tunelessly, emphasizing the last part of the verse with a small eruption from his cushioned seat.  Faera, who was trying to ignore the interlopers who had forced themselves into her prosperous world, scrunched up her nose in disgust, then turned back to dusting a gleaming bejeweled shield.  
<br />

<br />
"Thurgga... she... aftur me!" Groff pleaded, shaking Orgak's arm and disrupting a neat stack of weapons with a boisterous clang.  Mortified, he looked over his shoulder before turning back to Orgak.
<br />

<br />
"Whut, yous steps on hur tose agin? Ur stick hur in  brume closet?" Orgak questioned, with a grin on his face.
<br />

<br />
"No, no, no, not aftur like dat, like dis!" Groff complained, pursing his lips and making smacking "smootchie" sounds.
<br />

<br />
Orgak raised an eyebrow, as did several near by vendors and shoppers.  Ignoring the onlookers, Orgak grinned.  "Oooh... She's got swamp fevur!" 
<br />

<br />
"Der no time fer dat, Orgak!  Wez gots ta go!" Groff pleaded, exasperatedly.
<br />

<br />
Suddenly, Thurgga's voice rose above the din in a shout. "find rGoff... Find Gorff... Find Groff..."  Groff's eyes widened in terror.
<br />

<br />
"Wez gotsta GOOOO!" Groff whimpered, clearly now in a panic.  Suddenly, he sneezed.  And sneezed again.  And then a third time.  Rubbing furiously at his nose, he shook his head, confused.  Orgak's eyes widened.  Groff, now confused more than terrified, looked behind him again, trying to figure out what his friend was staring at.  Stretched out behind him and winding around the corner was a sparkling yellow swirl of magic.  Waving at it, he tried to make the path dissapate to no avail.  Exasperated and near his breaking point, Groff stood and waved furiously at the swirling magic, knocking over several neat stacks of gear and making such a clamor that a couple of browsing shoppers made a hasty retreat from Faera's booth to a safe distance.  
<br />

<br />
"Ok, enough!" Faera growled, grabbing both Trolls by the scruffs of their necks.  "Thanks for stopping by, but you two have to go!  Bring me some more silks and rusty weapons or something the next time you're in the area... Don't hurry back.... the Exit is THAT WAY!" she said, pushing both of them out of the booth and toward the exit to the Nexus, several rough knuckled barbarians stepping forward to block any re-entry attempt.
<br />

<br />
Groff nodded as the Magical Path disolved when he stepped out from under the roofing of Faera's stall.  Grabbing Orgak by the elbow, he began to drag the shaman toward the exit, Orgak feebly protesting and reaching out toward the riches of the bazaar as they went.
<br />

<br />
As they pushed and shoved their way through the conjested hall leading to the Nexus, Groff broke into a full run, loosening his grip on Orgak in favor of putting as much ground as possible between himself and the Ogre girl.  With a heavy sigh, Orgak stopped, threw one last glance toward the market zone, then waved his arms and mumbled a few words, channelling the spirit of wolf into his and Groff's feet, as they ran toward the sanctuary of the Plane of Knowledge and beyond.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=348308">Groff Gorespiller</a>
<br />
Troll Dread Lord
<br />
Expatriot of Grobb
