			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Orgak's toothy grin grew wider and wider, his eyes alight with joy as he galloped -- arms spread wide -- for the unsespecting Drogmor collected within the confines of the makeshift railed fence.  Hardly noticing, he careened through the gate, splintering in into countless shards of splintered wood.  By the time Flavaa and Groff had made their way to him -- Groff taking care not to aggravate his wounded backside -- Orgak had his arms wrapped around a lizard-like mount neck.  The reptile chewed away at a mouthful of feed as if he hadn't noticed.  
<br />

<br />
"Puppy" Orgak mumbled, his face buried into it's long scaled neck.  
<br />

<br />
Flavaa considered the spectacle and then regarded the lighthouse and turned to Groff "Shall we?"  
<br />

<br />
Groff heaved his usual sigh that meant he was about to be coerced into doing something he'd rather not do.  He turned his attention away from Orgak and shook his head.  "We'z be here less time dan it takez meh ta leak an' we'z alreddy in trubble."
<br />

<br />
Flavaa grabbed him by the arm and gave him a pull towards the lighthouse.  "I'm thinking we'll have better luck with the owner of those Drogs than we will pulling Orgak off of that one.  Let's go.  It'll be a blast!"
<br />

<br />
They rounded the lighthouse and came to the doorway that led inside.  Flavaa gave a snicker and whispered to Groff.  "This'll be easy!"  Suddenly, Flavaa's walk turned to a saunter as she made her way over to the gnome-pirate who was dusting and straighting his display of drums of various sizes and colors.  She moved like a serpent coming up from a basket to the call of a charmer's pipe.  As she drew closer, his eyes were on her.  Up and then down, up and back down, his gaze covered her from head to toe.  Once she knew she had his attention she removed the glove on her right hand with her teeth.  A line of drool was making its way from the gnome's bottom lip to the floor.  
<br />

<br />
Groff stayed behind so as not to draw attention to himself.  He watched the pathetic dinky pink creature succumb to Flavaa's wiles.  She tickled his chin, stood too close, and occasionaly brought her lips close enought to his that light barely shone through the gap.  Groff stepped back from the doorway, ducking to the side so as to go unnoticed when the Gnome led Flavaa out of the lighthouse and into a small cabin near the edge where the water met the side of the tiny isle.  He was holding a small green drum.  As soon as they dissappeared from sight and into the shanty, Groff made his way toward it casually.  He brandished his polearm and placed himself directly outside the window staying to the side so as not to be seen.  
<br />

<br />
Groff could hear the voices inside.  One was that of an eager Gnome stammering for words and the other was that of a dark elf, apparently with congestion, as her voice was deep and breathy.  Just a few moments later, Groff heard his cue.  The Gnome's head had bumped into the windowsill which was at the head of his tiny bed.  Groff paused for a moment to catch Flavaa's attention.  She was straddling the Gnome and had pinned his arms to his sides with her knees.  She looked up at the window, a very large Troll silhouette blocking the light, and then regarded the Gnome with a look of disgust and said, "There's only one problem."
<br />

<br />
"What.. wha... what's that?"  He gasped, not yet noticing the forboding image in the window behind him.  
<br />

<br />
Groff readied his polearm's hilt to hit the gnome square on the noggin and proclaimed "It's a MAAAN baby!!!"  Those were the last words the Drogmor vendor in Gunthank heard before waking up much later with a very painful headache.
<br />

<br />
Flavaa shivered as wave of disgust made it's way through her body.  She lept out the window deftly, small green drum in tow.  The two bandits made short work of the distance between the shack and where Orgak was surely still fawning over the lizard.  The dark elf brought her self over the gate swiftly shortly before Groff simply smashed it to bits with his polearm.  Orgak regarded them with surprise.  "Aawww... do we'z hafta go?  Meh wunt ta stay wit da lizzy."  
<br />

<br />
"He's yours!  Catch!"  Flavaa underhanded the drum in his direction.  It hit him square in the chest and bounced to the ground where the Shaman considered it, confused.
<br />

<br />
"Wut youz mean?  Meh not wunt dummy drum drum, meh wuntz lizzy.  Meh named her 'n everting!"  
<br />

<br />
"Dat's FOR deh lizzy youz ninc.. ninecom... YOU'Z BIG DUMMY!  NOW LETZ GIT OUTTA HERE!"   Groff was absentmindedly rubbing his rear.  
<br />

<br />
Orgak bent and grabbed the drum.  He looked it over not understanding.  He turned it upside down, to the side, and then in frustration tried to put the hollowed end over the lizard's snout as if to stuff him in it.  Groff got behind the unfortunate lizard and began to push from the other end.  
<br />

<br />
"Um.. boys..."  Flavaa said, not believing the spectacle in front of her.  Orgak had one arm around the Drogmor's neck pulling it's face into the bottom of the drum with the other hand while groff had both feet planted, pushing with all his might from the rear.  
<br />

<br />
Groff's foot slipped on a loose stone and he stumbled forward, one arm completely dissappearing into the mount.  At this point, Flavaa intervened and put a stop to the effort.  "I don't think that's how it works."  
<br />

<br />
Groff gave his arm a tug to free it, regarded it with a sniff and shrugged.  Flavaa was looking pale for a Dark Elf.  "Darn, meh losta bracer!"  
<br />

<br />
Out of brilliant ideas for working the magical drum, he began to bounce his forehead off of the skinned top.  "Stupy stupy stupy drum... wy not youz work"  The third time his head met with the drum, the drogmor was animated it seemed to actually sink into the ground and out of sight. 
<br />

<br />
"That's it! Now let's GOOOOO!  Make with the SoW already!"  Flavaa was glancing nervously about and pleading with the Shaman to get moving. 
<br />

<br />
Running across a pad of air between their feet and the water, away from the danger of being discovered as Drogmor thieves, the trio ran for the beach to the West.  Empty undead eye sockets followed them from the deep as they passed overhead.  Orgak was out of breath and panting, but too excited not to exclaim "Meh... callz... her... Shugarfoot!"<br />_________________<br />65 Troll Shaman 
<br />
LFHC (Looking for Home City)
<br />
